INTRODUCTION

There are quite a few good 3D rendering packages for the Amiga.

These programs draw, or 'render',  a picture by figuring out how it should
look, given the subject matter, a camera angle, and lighting conditions.

For example,  a rendering program might be told to draw a house from the
vantage point of the driveway, with the primary light source being the sun
at some angle in the sky. The rendering program computes what the scene
should look like, given this information, and creates a painting.

Most of the rendering programs can go one step further and create a sequence of paintings that follow a progression in time. A car might be shown
driving up to the house. Each successive painting shows the car a bit closer.
When these painting are shown in quick succession, the car moves and you
have created an animation.

The subject matter, the items that are rendered in these paintings, are
called "objects". Houses, cars, and people are all examples of objects.

It is obvious that the tasks of designing these objects is a very important
part of the rendering and animation process.

Enter 3-Demon.

3-Demon is an object editor. Use it to create the objects that the other
programs render.

3-Demon is both powerful and easy to use. You can create any shape of 
object with any number of colors, and you work with the mouse extensively
in an intuitive, "What You See Is What You Get", environment.

Once you have created an object, 3-Demon can store it to disk in the various
formats that the other programs read.

