BUILDING BLOCKS IN A 3D WORLD

Before we do anything else, it's a good idea to cover the basics of 3D graphics
and how objects are represented in the 3D world.

THE 3D WORLD

In the real, three dimensional, world outside, things can be described in
terms of their width, height, and depth. And, their position might be
described in terms of how far they are North, East, and Up. For example, 
Harry's refrigerator is 3 feet by 6 feet by 2 feet and we can find it on the
map at three hundred feet North, two hundred feet East, twenty feet Up (in
his tree house), relative to City Hall. When Harry walks out of City Hall, 
he knows he can walk three hundred feet North, two hundred feet East, and
climb twenty feet up a rope to get that bologna sandwich.

What this all says is we can use three numbers to describe where things are
in the three dimensional world. These three numbers tell where a point is
relative to an origin. In the example of Harry's refrigerator, the origin is
City Hall. These three numbers are called the 'coordinates' that describe a
point.

AXES

Imagine three lines running through City Hall. One runs due North. This 
is called the North Axis. One runs Due East. This is the East Axis. And, 
one runs straight up. This is the up axis.

When we give a position as three distances, we are actually giving it in
terms of three distances along the three axes. Harry's refrigerator is 300
feet along the North axis, 200 feet along the East axis, and 20 feet along 
the Up axis.

THE 3-DEMON WORLD

In a 3-Demon's world, the three axes are not called North, East, and Up.
Instead, they are called X, Y, and Z. The origin isn't City Hall, it's just
the center of things, often the center of the screen. Instead of feet, we
just use plain numbers as a unit of measure. So, if the coordinates for
Harry's refrigerator are 300, 200, 20, then it is 300 in the X directions, 200 in
Y direction and 20 in the Z direction.

				4

REPRESENTING OBJECTS IN 3D

The object you create is a recreation of a real world physical entity. Examples of objects would be a cube, a sphere, a chicken.

In the real world,  these objects have mass. To describe them accurately
involves knowing what they are made of on the inside as well as on the
outside. However, if we are only interested in what an object looks like, we
can describe it purely in terms of its outer surface. Yes, a car has an engine
under the hood, but if all we see is the paint job, windows, and wheels, 
that's all we need to know about.

So, as far as graphics programs are concerned, objects are defined not by
what they are in the real world, but by what their outer surface looks like.
These surfaces can be plain and flat, or complex, like swiss cheese.

POLYGONS

We construct this outer surface using polygons. For instance, a polygon
cube is composed of six squares, one square for each of the cube's six sides.

A red cube is made of six red squares, one for each side.

				5

POINTS

But how is a polygon described? The best way to describe it is as a set of
connecting points. A square is made up of four points.

Now we need to describe a point. This is where all the talk about defining
a position in 3D space comes in. A point is defined by three coordinates -
one for each of the three axes X, Y,  and Z.

If we were to construct Harry's refrigerator out of polygons, the front bottom left hand corner would have a point at 300, 200, 20. The right front
bottom corner would be at 300, 203, 20.

Fortunately, although all the points can be defined as X, Y, and Z numbers, 
3-Demon never requires that you deal with these numbers directly. Instead, 
you can simply grab a point with the mouse and move it. After all, when
Harry had Whabam Bros Moving put the fridge in his tree house, he didn't
say, "Put it at 330, 200, 20." He said, "Put it in the tree house. Don't forget
to hook up the ice maker."

So, a polygon is made up of a bunch of points. When one of the points is
moved, the polygon's shape changes. This is how objects are edited in
3-Demon.

TRIANGLES

There is a problem with polygons. It has to do with moving a point in a
polygon. If a point that is part of a polygon moves out of the plane of the
polygon, it creates a strangely twisted polygon moves out of the plane of the
polygon, it creates a strangely twisted polygon. Say that a sheet of paper
resting on your desk is a polygon. It has four points, one for each corner. If
you move one of the points by lifting a corner of the page up off the desk, 
the paper bends. You can, however, crease the paper between to opposite
corner points to create two triangles, each of which is flat. Then, if you
move the same point, the two triangles on either side of the crease will stay
flat. In fact, you can move any of the points and the two triangles will stay
flat.

Triangles are magic. You can move any point of a triangle without creating
a 'twisted' triangle. So, once you've broken a polygon into triangles, you
are safe to move any points.

Since 3-Demon places so much emphasis on editing points, given the magic
of triangles, it makes sense to outlaw all polygons larger than triangles.
Larger polygons can simply be build out of triangles.

				6

So, 3-DEMON does not talk about building objects our of polygons. Instead, 
3-Demon works with triangles.

BACK FACES

There are two sides, or faces, to a triangle, just as there are two sides to a
piece of paper. Normally, when you are building an object out of triangles, 
all of the inward faces will never be seen. It is the outward faces that are
given colors and are drawn. For example, we build a sphere out of triangles.
Each triangle has two sides. One faces out, it represents the surface of the 
sphere. The other side of the triangle faces in. Nobody can see it. This
inward side is called a 'back face'. With an object like our sphere, there is
no need to display the back face.

There are times when you might want to display back faces. You could
have a triangle floating free in space.

3-Demon has several tools for working with back faces. You decide if you
wish to see the back faces. You can flip the back face of a triangle to the
front. And, you can add a triangle that covers the back face of a triangle
with a front facing triangle.

LINES

In addition to triangles, you can work with straight lines in your object. A
line has two end points.

SHARED POINTS

Several triangles and lines can share a single point. This has a powerful use.
When a shared point is moved, all triangles and lines that use the same point 
will change shape as the shared point is moved to a new location.

SURFACES

As you build objects with 3-Demon, you will want to paint them. You can 
select a color for the surface of each triangle that makes up an object. In
addition, you can describe how that color behaves. How does it reflect
light? Is it transparent?

				7

Each object owns a set of surfaces. Each triangle, line, and point that make
up this object is painted with one of these surfaces.

Example surfaces might be "red brick", "steel", and "toe nail".

THE OBJECT HIERARCHY

Often, an object will have a moving part. For example, Bruno the dog has
a tail. It is easier to make Bruno's tail wag if it is a separate object, even
though it is attached to old Bruno. However, when Bruno moves, the tail
has to move with him. as a separate object, it won't.

It would be nice if there were some relationship between the two objects
that said when Bruno moves, the tail moves with him, but when the tail
moves, Bruno doesn't move with the tail.

Such a relationship doesn't exist. There is the HIERARCHY of objects. One
object can belong to another object. Using this capability, we have the tail
object belong to the Bruno object.

An object that belongs to another object is often called its child. And, the
object which owns this child is called the parent. A parent object can have
any number of children. Each child can, in turn, have its own children.

