THE 3D ENVIRONMENT

Before you start to make objects, it would be a good idea to discuss the
3-Demon environment - how you, the artist, interface with the three dimensional object you are creating.

THE MAIN VIEW

When Pierre the sculptor fashions a lump of clay, he has to see exactly
what he is doing. If there is a particular part that he wishes to work on, 
he moves the clay around so that he sees that part. Naturally, he orients
himself so that the view gives him the best possible feedback of what he is
doing with his hands.

For example, when working hard on a bust of his favorite sculptor, he feels
the need to make the nose just a little less prominent. To get the best view
of what he is about to do, he turns the bust sideways so he is looking at
the face in profile. Then, as he scrapes at the nose with a scalpel he can
see exactly what he is doing.

You can see that if he were to reshape the nose while looking at the bust
head on, he would have a very hard time gauging what he is doing. The
length of the nose would be represented by how far from Pierre it is rather
than how wide. From a side view, though, he can easily gauge the length
of the nose.

				9

3-Demon works much the same way. You are a sculptor creating an object.
You can view the object you are working on from any angle so that what
you see is really what the object looks like.

This rendition of the object is called the Main View. It occupies most of
3-Demon's screen.

As you work on the object, you are free th change your orientation so that
you can see the object from whatever angle makes the most sense, much
like Pierre walking around his lump of clay.

				10

And, where Pierre uses his fingers to push and prod the clay, you use the
mouse to perform the same task.

Sadly, there's nothing that takes the place of that gallon of cheap table wine
that Pierre always has on hand for inspiration.

Editing tends to be straightforward because you see what you are doing.

If you are working on that bust of Pierre and recognize that the nose really
should be more prominent, you position the bust so it is in profile (just as
he did) facing right, then drag the nose right, extending it.

When moving points, orient yourself so that the points will be moving up
and down, right and left.

Similarly, when painting, you orient yourself so you can see the parts you 
wish to color. Then you click on a triangle to give it a selected color.

The whole process of creating and editing a three dimensional object in
3-Demon involves moving the object around to get a good view of it, then
working within that view.

THE DEPTH VIEW

Pierre knows how far away the piece of clay he is working on is because he's
got his arm extended. We don't have that physical feedback because our
mouse is purely two dimensional.

When we create a new point, it is not enough to just point and click with the
mouse. This only tells us where the new point is in up-down and left-right
coordinates. What it doesn't say is how far away the point is.

So, an additional view is provided that will show us how far away the parts
we are working on are and let us specify how far away new additions should
be.

				11

The Depth View shows how far away everything is. And, with the Depth
View, you can specify the distance you wish to work at.

The Depth View exists to the right of the Main View at the top of the
3-Demon screen.

We will learn how to use the Depth View later in this chapter.

So, we've got a Main View where we do all our work and a Depth View
that helps us deal with depth.

The rest of this chapter is a tour of the 3-Demon commands that manipulate
the two views. It would be a good idea to have 3-Demon running while you
read this.

