CHANGING THE PERSPECTIVE

To create the effect of perspective, 3-Demon uses two pieces of information:
The position of an imaginary eye and the position of an imaginary screen.
3-Demon computes what an object would look like as seen from the position
of the eye, and draws that on the screen. Imagine that the eye is an X-Ray source, shining through the object. The X-Ray image of the object is
projected on the screen.

An object that is closer to the eye will "project" larger on the screen.

3-Demon lets you reposition the eye and screen. To the right of the Depth
View are two icons that can be dragged up and down.

The Eye

This represents the position of the eye. Move it close to the object and
things get very distorted, much like a fish eye lens. Objects that are close
are drawn very large, while far away objects stay small. If the Eye is far
from the object, it behaves much more like a telephoto lens. In this case, 
objects that are close are drawn just about the same size as objects that
are far.

The Screen

				16

This represents the position of the imaginary screen the objects are 'projected' onto.

Play with the eye and screen icons around to see how they affect they view.

Shifting and Scaling the View

You can also shift the center of the display away from the origin. And, you
can change the scale of the view.

As it turns out, neither of these need to be done often, if at all, so their
commands are only available on request. To access them, go to the View 
menu and select the View Control Box option in the Display menu item.

A window will open up in the bottom left hand corner of the screen.

This is the View Control Box. It can be turned on and left running or shut
down at anytime. It has the commands to shift and scale the view.

Scale

This changes the display size of the viewed objects. All the way to the right
and they are full size. Drag it to the left to make them appear smaller.

				17

This does not actually change the size of the objects. It only changes the
drawing scale.

X Shift

Drag this to the right to move the center of the world to the right. Once
again, this is not moving the objects themselves to the right. Instead, it is
moving where we are looking to the left, so everything appears to move to
the right.

Y Shift

Drag this to the right to move the center of the world up. Once again, this
is not moving the objects themselves, only shifting our view.

Z Shift

Drag this to the right to move the center of the world closer to the viewer
 (the eye).

Notice that each time you change one of these the Main and Depth views
are refreshed. If you close the View Control Box, the changes made will not
be lost.

