Distance and Grab Range

When you add new triangles or lines to your object, you need to say how
far away they are in depth. The vertical and horizontal positions are given
by the mouse, but the depth is not.

So, using the Depth View, we specify the depth. In addition to the Eye
and Screen icons, there are two more icons that can be slid up and down.
These are the Distance and Grab Range sliders.

The Distance Slider

Drag this to determine the depth that new parts are placed at. Think of it
as a sheet of glass that can be dragged between you and the screen. New
points are painted on this sheet of glass. But, when the sheet of glass moves
again, the points stay where they are, they don't move with it.

Notice that the Distance Slider is accompanied by a solid black line through
the Depth View to show where it lies.

The Grab Range Slider

In the Depth View both the top and the bottom of the display have a
pattern of white dots masking the picture. What these say is that anything
under the white dotes can not have their points moved. Only points between
the two banks of dots can be grabbed. The area between is called the Grab
Range. The Grab Range makes editing easier because it lets you isolate
only the portions of the view that you wish to edit.

This slider sets the Grab Range:

				19

This sets the two sides of the Grab Range. This is done by having the Grab
Range be centered on the Distance slider.

Play with the two sliders to see how you can manipulate the Grab Range.
Notice that only the points of the test object that are within the Grab
Range are illuminated.

THE DEPTH CONTROL BOX

Sometimes, it would be useful to give precise numbers for the Drag Range, 
Distance, Eye, and Screen. To access these a window that lets you edit
these, go to the View menu and select the Depth Control Box option in
the Display command.

A window should open up in the bottom left hand corner of the screen.

This is the Depth Control Box. Like the View Control Box, it can be turned
