ALTERING THE DRAW STYLE

You can control how 3-Demon draws an object in the Main View. The rendering of points, triangles, and the triangle edges can be selectively turned
on and off. The drawing of triangle back faces can also be turned on and 
off. And, you can decide whether objects be drawn as shaded gray objects, 
or in color without shading.

The commands to set the draw style are found in the Draw Style menu
item of the View menu.

EDGES

This flag determines whether the edges of triangles should be drawn. When
it is off, the triangles appear borderless. When it is on, they are drawn in
black if they belong to an object that is currently being worked on or white
if they belong to any other object.

If Edges are turned on, but Triangles are turned off, you end up with a 
wire frame display which has the one slight advantage of taking a little less
time to draw.

POINTS

This determines whether the points should be drawn. Only the points of
the object selected that are within the Grab Range are drawn. If you find
the points obnoxious to look at, turn them off. However, they are useful for
editing because they indicate where the points that you can drag are.

				21

TRIANGLES

This selects whether triangles should be filled or not.  If they aren't,  you
get a wire frame object (or nothing if Edges is also turned off).

BACK FACES

Every triangle has two faces. Normally, only the face we are intended to
see is shown. When you create a triangle by drawing it, the side facing
you is automatically set to be the front face. If you then move around to 
view it from the back, you see the back face. With solid objects, like cubes
spheres, and chickens, you never see the back faces because they always face
the inside of the object.

By default, back faces are not displayed for two reasons. Displaying them
doubles the display time on the average. And, it's possible for slight errors
in the display of an object to occur because a back face managers to stomp
on a front face.

There aren't too many reasons to display back faces, because there are two
commands in the Edit menu that take care of most issues. One command
creates a front face to cover a triangle's back face. The other flips a
triangle so the two faces are reversed.

But, there will always be some sneak who wants to snoop around behind 
things, so the option to display back faces is available.

SHADED

This gives you the option of having the objects drawn shaded. The primary
purpose of this is to give a better feel for the three dimensional nature of
an object. Here is an object drawn shaded and unshaded:

				22

There are limitations to the shading. There are no colors. Instead, each
object is drawn on a gray scale ranging from white to black. And, the light
sources can not be positioned. There are two lights at opposite sides of each 
object. This guarantees that we don't have one side shaded and the other
side in the dark.

