QUANATIZING

Quanatization is a powerful tool for cleaning up slop in an object. What it
does is resolve a point to an imaginary grid. You set the spacing of the
lines in that grid. This spacing is also called the resolution. When a point
is quanatized,  it is shifted to the closest cross point in that grid. Here's a
triangle before and after Quanatization:

You can quanatize points to any resolution.

Quanatization in 3-Demon is complicated by the fact that you may wish to
quanatize with the reference grid being positioned in the coordinate system
of the object,  the world,  or the view.

So, when you select the quanatize command,  you are given three reference 
options: World,  Object,  and View,  with a fourth option to simply turn off
Quanatization,  Off.

If you choose Object,  points you quanatize will be quanatized against a grid
that is also positioned within that object. If you have scaled or rotated the
object with a transformation list*, these will not effect the Quanatization.

If you choose World,  the Quanatization will be based on world coordinates, 
rather than the coordinates of the object itself. If the object has no transformations applied to it,  the result will be the same as with the Object
command. But,  if the object has been altered by some transformations
(you have created a transformation list for it that rotates, scales, or moves
it), the Quanatization will be applied to the result of those transformations, 
rather than the object itself.

*The use of transformations is covered later in its own chapter. Don't be
concerned if you don't know what a transformation is.

				43

Finally, the View option uses a Quanatization grid that is oriented to the
view. The Quanatization is lined up with the angle that you view the object
from. Rotate, scale, or shift the view,  and the Quanatization changes with
it.
For the first three choices, a window opens letting you set the Quanatization.
Then, you select the points and triangles to quanatize simply by clicking on
them. If you click on a point,  it alone will be quanatized. If you click on a
triangle,  the three points at its border will be quanatized.

QUANATIZING NEW POINTS

After you are done QUANATIZING,  the Quanatization will stay in effect unless
you turn it off. If you go back to adding new points,  and the new points
will be quanatized.
So, if you'd rather not have that happen, remember to turn Quanatization
off with the Off command.

