SURFACES

As you build objects with 3-Demon, you will want to paint them. You can
select a color for each triangle, line, and point that makes up an object. In
addition, you can describe how that color behaves. How does it reflect 
light? Is it transparent?

So, there is a need to describe both the color and how it behaves. All this
information in bundled into something called a "surface".

You can assign surfaces to triangles, lines, and points.

Each object owns a set of surfaces and each triangle, line, and point within
that object is painted with one of these surfaces.

For example, an object made of bricks and steel would have two surfaces
defined. One, called "red brick", would describe a red color and the surface characteristics of brick (opaque, matte finish, etc.) The other surface, 
called "steel", would be gray and highly reflective. All triangles painted
brick would have the brick surface selected. The steel triangles would have
the steel surface selected. Should new triangles that are made of glass be
added to the object, a surface describing glass would be added to the set of
surfaces, and the glass triangles would select it.

