THE COLOR KNOBS

There are six knobs that you can grab and drag to change the color of a
surface.

RED, GREEN, AND BLUE

The left three knobs describe the color as a composite of three pieces of
information: the quantities of red, green and blue that make up the color.
This is actually how colors are described inside the Amiga.

The R knob stands for Red, the G knob stands for Green, and we haven't 
yet figured out what B stands for.

You can alter a color simply by grabbing a knob and turning it.

You will probably find that describing a color in terms of its Red, Green, 
and Blue parts is confusing at times. Hence the need for a second system:

HUE, SATURATION, AND INTENSITY

This is a much more intuitive method for describing colors.

Hue is like a color wheel. Grab it and rotate it. The color will gradually
change from red to purple to blue to green to yellow to red again.

Saturation describes how distinct the selected color is. When saturation is
turned on full, the color is bold. As the saturation is turned down, the color
becomes blander and blander, eventually blending into a wash of gray.

Intensity determines how dark the color is. It is analogous to a light dimmer.
With intensity turned completely off, a color becomes simply black. As the
intensity is turned up, it gets brighter and brighter, just like turning up that
light dimmer. For those romantic, candle lit colors, have intensity turned
most of the way down.

The best way to understand Hue, Saturation, and Intensity is to experiment
with them. Notice that as these parameters are changed, the Red, Green, and
Blue values are updated.

SURFACE CHARACTERISTICS

There is a collection of sliders in the bottom half of the window that adjust
how the surface behaves when exposed to light. Depending on the rendering
program you are using, all, some, or none of these parameters make it into

				49

that program's file format. If the renderer supports a surface feature, then
it will be found in the file. Of course, all of these are saved in the 3-Demon
file format.

AMBIENT LIGHT

This represents how much light the surface emits, regardless of where the
light sources are. This is useful when you can't afford to model every single
light source in a scene, but you'd like to wave a magic wand and say "there's
this much light hitting these objects." For example, a starship in the night
sky is illuminated by thousands of stars, but rather than computing how
much light from each star hits the ship, you categorize that as ambient light
and simply state how much ambient light there is. Objects can be made to
glow in the dark by turning up their ambient light.

DIFFUSE REFLECTION

When a surface has a matte finish, it reflects light in all directions. It looks
dull, as opposed to shinny. This is called diffuse reflection. A piece of normal
paper (not the glossy magazine variety) is diffuse. On the other hand, a
mirror, which reflects in only one direction, has no diffuse reflection.

To increase the diffuse reflection, pull this slider to the right. This will
increase the brightness of this surface in the presence of light. All the way
to the right, and it'll behave like a day-glo sticker. All the way to the left, 
and it will be black (if the other reflection values are also turned down.)

SPECULAR REFLECTION

				50

When a surface has a glossy finish, this is due to specular reflection. Specularity reflected light bounces off the surface at the same angle it came in
at. Specular reflection is what makes a mirror work. Some dishwashing
liquid manufactures promote their products by showing how the specular
reflection of a plate increases dramatically after washing.

To increase specular reflection, pull this slider to the right. An object with
glossy highlights would have the specular reflection all the way to the right.
A non glossy, flat surface would have it all the way to the left.

METALICITY

Specular reflection can be very sharp or it can be dull. The duller it is, the
more it is like diffuse lighting. The sharper it is, the more it behaves like a
mirror. This is often called Metalicity because metal surfaces tend to have
sharp specular reflection.

Remember that if your renderer does not support this attribute, there is
little point in playing with it.

REFLECTION

This slider simply states how reflective the surface is. All the way to the
right and the surface reflects a lot of light, all the way to the left and it
doesn't.

TRANSPARENCY

If your renderer supports transparent and partly transparent surfaces, this
slider comes into play. Glass is completely transparent and the slider should

				51

be all the way to the right. Rose colored glasses are somewhere in the
middle. Most surfaces are opaque, no light can go through them, and the
slider is all the way to the left.

REFRACTION

Refraction is a characteristic of transparent solids. When light passes from
one transparent object to another of differing consistency, it bends. Did
you ever notice that when somebody stands in a pool, the part of them
below the water seems to be at an odd angle to the part above the water?
That's refraction at work.

Refraction gives that wonderful distortion associated with looking through
a glass ball or any glass object.

All the way to the right, the refraction slider represents a strong index of
refraction. The index becomes nothing at the far left. Glass would be two
thirds to the right, water about one third to the left, thin air just about at
the far left.

SPECIAL ID

There are almost certainly other surface characteristics that have not been
included. Should a renderer that needs some additional obscure information
come about, the Special ID parameter offers a way of providing additional
information.

Each triangle in a Sculpt 3D object can have one of several surface types
assigned to it. At the time of this writing, these types are 0 for dull, 1 for
shiny, 2 for mirrored, 3 for luminous, and 4 for glass. And, 128 is added
to the number if Phong shading is enabled. When 3-Demon loads a Sculpt
3D object, it stores these numbers in the Special ID field. The sliders
are adjusted appropriately, but you can adjust the Sculpt texture simply

