WORKING WITH OBJECTS

Although the primary focus with 3-Demon is editing within an individual
object, there's plenty that can be done with objects as a whole, and some
of these operations augment the editing process.

BUILDING AN OBJECT OUT OF OTHER OBJECTS

It's useful to break an object you're working on into separate parts, or
objects. Editing operations can be performed on each independently. When
each part is complete, the last step is to position all of the parts into their
proper places, then combine them into one object.

For example, to build a car you might design a car body object and a wheel
object. When both are done, four copies of the wheel object are positioned
in the wheel wells and combined with the body object to make one complete
car.

You might build a library of parts saved on disk. Call up appropriate parts
as building blocks for putting together a more complex object. These can
be everything from simple geometric parts - spheres, cubes, and cones - to
trees, wheels, and chicken parts.

With this method of building an object out of several parts, there are several
things we need to be able to do:

	Scale an object larger or smaller so it's the proper size.
	Grab an object and move it anywhere.
	Orient an object so it faces in the right direction.
	Combine two objects into one.
	Make an identical copy of an object.
	Save and load objects to disk.
	Create a new object.
	Select an object for editing from the Edit menu.
	Delete an object.
	
