WORKING WITH AN OBJECT HIERARCHY

3-Demon supports hierarchy objects. While working in this manner is not
absolutely necessary for creating objects,  it is an elegant approach.

Here are the rules for hierarchial objects in 3-Demon:

	One object can be the parent of several objects.

	When a parent object is moved, all of its children move with it.

	When a child moves, it does not effect its parent.

	The HIERARCHY can be any depth. An object can have grandchildren
	and great-grandchildren.

For example, we have Bruno the dog and his tail. Bruno is the parent object, the
tail is the child object. When Bruno is moved, the tail moves with him. But when
the tail is wagged by rotating it side to side, Bruno is not violently wagged
along with his tail.

In order to work with a HIERARCHY of objects, we need to be able to:

	Create an object that is a child of another object. We start by
	creating the parent object,  then moving on down as we build the
	children.

	Load an object from disk and make it a child of another object.

	Edit where an object is in the object HIERARCHY. If an object isn't
	where it should be in the HIERARCHY or we need to do some major
	redesign of the HIERARCHY, we should have a way to do it.

Needless to say, there is a command for each of the above requirements.

				67

