QUANATIZING AN OBJECT

Quanatization is a powerful tool for cleaning up slop in an object. You can use
it from the Edit menu on a point by point basis,  or here to clean up the entire
object at once.

What Quanatization does is resolve a point to an imaginary grid. You determine
the spacing of the lines in that grid. this spacing is called the Quanatization
resolution. When the point is quanatized, it is shifted to the closest cross
point in the grid. Here's an object before and after Quanatization:

You can quanatize points to any resolution.

Quanatization in 3-Demon is complicated by the fact that you may wish to
quanatize with the reference grid being positioned in the coordinate system of
the object, the world, or the view.

So, you are given three reference options: World,  Object,  and View.

				70

If you choose Object, points you quanatize will be quanatized against a grid that
is also positioned within the object. If you have scaled or rotated the object
with a transformation list, these will not effect the Quanatization.

If you choose World, the Quanatization will be based on world coordinates,  rather
than the coordinates of the object itself. If the object has no transformations
applied to it, the result will be the same as with the Object command. But, if
the object has been altered by some transformations (you have created a
transformation list for it), the Quanatization will be applied to the result of
those transformations, rather than the object itself.

Finally, the View uses a Quanatization grid that is oriented to the view. The
Quanatization is lined up with the angle that you view the object from. Rotate, 
scale, or shift the view, and the Quanatization changes with it.

For each choice, a window opens letting you set the Quanatization. Then, the
entire object is quanatized.

