TRANSFORMING AN OBJECT

Although it is possible to edit an object simply by grabbing points and moving
them in space, sometimes it's necessary to perform an operation that moves the
entire object, often in some complex manner. For example, you may have a head
object that you'd like to stick on a body object, but, sadly, the head is facing
in the wrong direction. And, the head is just a little too small in proportion
to the body. What you need to do is turn the entire head around, make it just a
bit bigger, and move it into position on the body.

THE TRANSFORMATIONS

There is a set of three operations that can be applied to an entire object to
do this sort of magic. One operation rotates objects in space, one scales their
size, and one simply move them. These operations are called "transformations"
because they transform the object in some way. The Move command in the object
menu is a simply example of a transformation. it takes the object and
transforms all points by adding constant X,  Y,  and Z values to them.

Here's how each of the transformation work:

MOVE

This is the simplest. It is often called 'translation'. To move, or translate, an
object, offset values for the X,  Y,  and Z directions are given. These are then
added to the X,  Y,  and Z coordinates of all of the points in the object. So, to
move an object forward by 100 in the X axis, the X move coordinate would be set
to 100, while the Y and Z coordinates would be 0,  for no movement in those
directions.

SCALE

This transformation multiplies the X,  Y,  and Z coordinates of a point by X,  Y, 
and Z scaling factors. For example, to make an object half size, the X,  Y,  and Z
scaling factors would all be 0.5. Then, when multiplied against the object, all
points would have half their original values. To make things a little more
sophisticated (and therefore confusing), you are not required to have similar
scaling factors in all three directions. You can stretch an

				73

object along one axis by having the scaling factor on that axis be 2, while the
scaling factor on the other two axis is 1.

ROTATE

Rotating an object in in 3d space is not as simple as rotating in two
dimensions. In two dimensions (a flat sheet of paper), you can simply say, 
"Rotate by 35 degrees" and your object turns in a circle by that amount. But in
three dimensions, it can rotate around any arbitrary axis. It could be "flip
over backwards" or "turn sideways". One way to deal with this is to define a
rotation as being composed of three separate rotations, each around one of the
axis. The way 3-Demon rotates an object in 3d space is to rotate it first a
given amount around the X axis,  then a given amount around the Y axis, then a
given amount around the Z axis.

Bake to our problem about the head and the body.

	Rotate First, a rotation transformation would be applied to the head.
	A rotation of 180 degrees around the Y axis (which is up and down, so
	the head would swivel from front to back) and rotations of 0 around the
	X and Z axes would orient the head directly.

	Scale Then, scaling factors of, say 1.1 would be applied against the
	X,  Y,  and Z axis and a scaling transformation performed to make the
	head just a little bigger.

	Move Finally, a move transformation with the proper offsets in the X,  Y, 
	and Z directions would place the head squarely on the shoulders.

USING TRANSFORMATIONS

3-Demon lets each object have its own set of transformations. You create this
set, and it is composed of any number of transformations in any order.

				74

To create and edit the transformations that belong to an object, select
'Transform' in the Object menu. Then, click on the object you wish to edit. A
Transform window should open for that object:

THE TRANSFORMATION LIST

In the right hand box is a list of transformations. We'll call this the
"Transformation List". The transformations are listed from top to bottom in the
order in which they are applied to the object. In the case shown here, the
object is first moved, then scaled, then rotated.

				75

MENU COMMANDS

To add a new transformation to this list, move the mouse to the top left hand
corner of the screen, click on the right mouse button, and pull down the menu.
There are six choices:

	TRANSFORM
	Add
	Delete
	Move
	Open
	Save
	Center

ADD

Select this to add a new transformation to the Transformation List. There are
four choices:

	TRANSFORM
	Add		Move
	Delete		Scale
	Move		Rotate
	Open		Move, Rotate, Move
	Save
	Center

				76

The first three, Move, Scale, and Rotate, create a transformation of that type and
install it in the transformation list.

The fourth command, Move, Rotate, Move, creates two MOVE transformations with a
ROTATE transformation stuck in the middle. The first MOVE transformation will
automatically have X, Y,  and Z offsets installed that are calculated to move the
object to the center of the screen. The second has offsets that are the
inverse, they move the object back out to where it is. The ROTATE transformation
is initialized with no rotation.

An explanation:

When you rotate an object with the ROTATE transformation, it is rotated around
the origin. But if the origin is not the center of the object, it will look like
the object is orbiting around the origin, rather than spinning around its own
center.

The solution is to move the object to the origin, do the rotation, then move it
back out again. The Move, Rotate, Move command does just that. It create a MOVE
transformation that moves the object to the origin, a ROTATE transformation that
spins the object, then another MOVE transformation to move the object back to
its original position.

You can then rotate the object with the ROTATE transformation and the object
will spin around itself, no matter where it is located in space.

DELETE

Select this to remove the currently selected transformation in the list.

MOVE

You may wish to move a transformation from one point in the list to another.
Select the transformation you wish to move by clicking on it in the
Transformation List, then select this command, then click on the position in the
list you'd like the transformation placed.

OPEN

You can load a list of transformations from disk with this command. If you
already have some transformations, the new ones will be appended to the end of
the list.

				77

SAVE

You can save the list of transformations.

CENTER

You may wish to have your object centered squarely at the origin. It is easiest
to do rotation and scaling transformations on an object that is centered at the
origin, then use a move transformation to put it at its destination. The Center
command recomputes all of the points in the object and shifts them so it now
hovers around the origin. To compute just where to be, it uses one of two
methods, given as subitem choices that you must select.

With By Volume, the center of the object is calculated as being the central
point between the farthest reaches of the object. If you have an object with
lots of fine detail at one end, and one big triangle, the center will probably
end somewhere in the middle of the big triangle.

Withy By Density, the center of the object is calculated as being the average of
all the points, so an object with a high density of points at one end would have
its center biased there.

You can experiment with both methods and see which fits your object best.

THE TRANSFORMATION CONTROL BOX

When an item in the Transformation List is selected, the data about it is
displayed in the large box to the left. This we'll call the Transformation
Control Box. There are three styles of Transformation Control Box, one for each
of the transformation types:

				78

If there are no transformations in the list, this box will be empty. To create a
transformation, use the Add menu command described above.

At the top of all three Transformation Control boxes is a button that describes
what type of transform this is. Click on it to change the transform from MOVE
to SCALE to ROTATE.

MOVE

The MOVE command gives you three sliders and three number entry boxes. The
three number boxes display the current X,  Y,  and Z values that the MOVE
transformation offsets the object by.

If you wish to change one of these values, click on the number and edit it. When
you hit the return key, the MOVE transformation is updated and the main display
redraws with the object moved (if you click on the main display you'll see our
friend the weightlifter at work.)

There are also three sliders that can be grabbed to move the object. Grab a
slider, pull it to the left for a negative offset. The resulting value is
displayed in the number entry box and the object is redrawn. Notice that the
slider bounces back to the center, so you make the negative offset greater by
pulling it left again.

SCALE

Working with the SCALE transformation is very similar to MOVE. The control box
looks almost the same, with one obvious difference. There is a button called
LOCK. When LOCK is activated (which it is by default), the three scaling factors
(X, Y, and Z) are locked together. If you edit one, 

				79

the others are changed by the same amount, so the scaling is uniform in all
directions. Turn off LOCK, and all three must be edited separately.

Once again, there are the three number entry boxes. This time, the numbers are a
floating point values that are multiplied against the object to scale it. So, 
they are initialized to one, which results in no scaling. A value of two doubles
the object in size. A value of 0.33, or one third, shrinks the object to one
third size.

And, you can grab the sliders to change the scaling. Pulling a slider all the
way to the left decreases along that axis (or all three if LOCK is on) by
exactly one half while pulling all the way to the right doubles the size.

ROTATE

Like the other two, the ROTATE control box has three number entry boxes. These
correspond to the three axes the object is rotated around. Each is an angle
from 0 to 360 degrees.

You can also alter the three rotation axes by grabbing the circular knobs and
turning them. These knobs rotate the object relative to the current heading of
the object, so they don't simply alter the corresponding X, Y,  and Z rotation
values. This results in a more intuitive interface. You might think of this as
flying the object, where the rotations of X, Y,  and Z affect the heading of the
object, or 'airplane' just as Pitch, Yaw, and Foonleysplat would. Play with the
knobs to get a feel for how they affect the object's movement.

THE OBJECT'S NAME

In the top left hand side of the window, the object's name is displayed. If
you'd like, you can change it by clicking on it and editing it. Descriptive

				80

names like "dog" or "foot" are much more appropriate than "Object #N" which is
what the objects are named by default.

CONVERT

When you apply transformations to an object, the points in the object itself are
not changed. Instead, when the object is displayed, the transformations are
applied and the object looks like it have been transformed. *

Although it is not necessary, you may wish to make all the transformations you
are doing to the object permanent. Clicking on the CONVERT button changes all
of the points in the object to be what the transformations make it look like.
And,  the transformations are all initialized.

For example, once you have successfully sized, rotated, and moved the head onto
the body, you could hit the CONVERT button to permanently alter the head to be
what you see. Then, you could remove all of the transformations with the menu
Delete command because they would no longer be needed.

There's a very good reason for not having the transformations alter the points
directly. It avoids distorting the object through the accumulated numerical
errors of lot of transformations.

For example, suppose you want to make the head of our example very small, a pin
head. You use a scaling transformation that reduces it by a factor of one
hundred. The head had coordinates that were all between 0 and 100. They all
become either 0 or 1, because there are no fractions. Then, you change your mind
and decide to make it big again. This time, scaling up by a factor of one
hundred results in coordinates that are all 0 or 100, with nothing in between, so
now you have a block head. **

This is a gross example of what can go wrong, but even the slightest of errors
will accumulate over time and become unacceptable.

*You will notice that when you remove a transformation or change it from one
type to another, whatever it did to the object is cleared and the object reverts
to its former state.
**Admittedly, having a block head around is not as irritating as a pin head, but
in the 3D world we have limited patience with lower orders of intellect.

				81

By preserving the original coordinates and only using the transformations to
alter how the points are displayed, we avoid this problem.

In fact, you can have two transformations one after the other in the
Transformation List, the first scaling an object down by one hundred, the second
scaling it back up, and there will be no distortion introduced.

LOTS AND LOTS OF TRANSFORMATIONS

It's obvious that you can have lots of transformations in the Transformation
List, with multiple uses of each of the three types. This may not seem to make
sense at first. Why have several rotations when any conceivable rotation can be
done with one?

Depending on the ordering of the transformations, they will effect each other.
Two like transformations with a different transformation between them will not
combine to give the same result as if they were adjacent.

An example: Let's say our object is a planet. To simulate its orbit, we have a
Transformation List that goes ROTATE, MOVE, ROTATE.

The first ROTATE rotates the planet around its own North pole.

Then, the MOVE command moves it the distance of the planet to the sun it orbits
around.

The final ROTATE will now rotate it in that orbit, because the center of the
rotation has been moved to the sun.

Try it.

TRANSFORMATIONS AND CHILDREN OBJECTS

All child objects that belong to an object that is being transformed will be
transformed with it. But, when a child object is transformed, only its children
and not its parent object will be affected. This is very important. This is the
primary purpose behind having a hierarchy of objects.

Here's an example: A car is the object, a wheel belongs to it. When the car
moves, the wheel always moves with it. But when the wheel rotates and pivots, it
shouldn't affect the car.

				82

OPENING AND SAVING OBJECTS

From the Object menu objects can be opened (loaded) and saved on an individual
basis. And, since 3-Demon is designed to interface with other Amiga 3D programs, 
they can be in one of six different object file formats, including 3-Demon's.

You can use 3-Demon to create objects for five rendering programs. These are
VideoScape 3D, Sculpt 3D, Silver, Forms in Flight, and Gossett Graphics.

And, you can read objects created by 3-Demon and two other programs - VideoScape
3D and Sculpt 3D.

3-DEMON

You should always keep one copy of an object you are working on in the 3-Demon
format. You can not possibly lose anything by saving in this format, because
this is the format 3-Demon uses internally. Only when you are done and ready to
send your object to another program should you create a file in that program's
format.

Likewise, objects that are read in from other formats should be saved in the
3-Demon format until they are ready to be sent back.

LOADING 3-DEMON

To open a 3-Demon object, go to the Object menu and select the 3-Demon option in
the Open command. A file requester will open. It will display all 3-Demon
object files. These end with the extension ".object". Objects saved as part of
a project with the Save command in the Project menu can not be opened from
here, those files have the extension ".3demon".

Select the file you wish to open. For more on using the file requester, see the
chapter The File Requester.

The object will be opened.

SAVING 3-DEMON

To save an object in the 3-Demon format, go to the Object menu and select the
3-Demon option in the Save command. Then, click on the object you

				83

wish to save. Only this object, which includes all of its children, will be
saved.

A file requester will open. It will display only 3-Demon object files, these all
end with the extension ".object".

Select the file name you wish to save or type in a new file name. For more on
using the file requester, see the chapter The File Requester.

The object will be saved in the 3-Demon format. The transformation list and all
surfaces will be saved along with the triangles that make up the object.

VIDEOSCAPE 3D

Videoscape 3D itself does not have any facility for creating and editing
objects. However, it comes with some utilities for creating simple objects.
And, there is a large public domain library of VideoScape objects out there. So, 
3-Demon can open VideoScape objects as well as save them.

Just imagine, now you can put white walls on the Lotus.

At the time of this publication, VideoScape 3D only supports eight colors:
black, blue, blue-green, green, red, purple, yellow, and gray.

The original VideoScape 3D only supports six colors, blue-green, and purple are
missing.

LOADING VIDEOSCAPE 3D

To open a VideoScape 3D object, go to the Object menu and select the VideoScape
option in the Open command. A file requester will open. It will display all
