SCULPT 3D

Sculpt 3D has a lot of similarities with 3-Demon, so it's easy to pass objects
back and forth between the two.

Like 3-Demon, Sculpt only works with triangles.

Sculpt also allows an unlimited range of colors.

The only issue with Sculpt 3D is it doesn't recognize a difference between
front and back faces. This problem can be dealt with in several ways when
opening Sculpt files:

For every triangle that is loaded an additional triangle that faces in the
opposite direction is created. This ensures that every triangle is visible.
However, since there are twice as many triangles, the display time is increased.

Back faces can be turned on from the Draw Style command in the View menu. Now, 
3-Demon will draw all triangles, regardless of how they face. This creates the
same results as the previous solution, without doubling the size of the object.
However the back faces problem has not really been solved yet and programs like
VideoScape 3D that require the triangles properly oriented will still display
only about half of the triangles.

The object can be loaded without back faces being added or displayed. Then, the
Flip command in the Edit menu is used to flip all back faces so they face
forward. This provides by far the most satisfying results, but it requires some
extra effort on your part.

LOADING SCULPT 3D

To open a Sculpt 3D object, go to the Object menu and select the Sculpt 3D
option in the Open command. A file requester will open. It will display all
files that are in the Sculpt 3D format. These files end with the extension
