ADD

There are six ways to add to an object. These are given as submenu choices:

Triangles: Add triangles by simply clicking on the screen where you want the
end points to lie. Every three points creates a new triangle. If you click on a
point that already exists, it will be used, rather than creating a new one.

Polygons: This is almost the same as adding triangles, except the shape keeps
growing with each additional point added. To finish the polygon, click on the
first point.

Lines: Create lines by clicking on the screen where you want the end points to
be. Every two points creates a line.

Spun: Use this to create a spun object by defining an outline, then spinning it
around the axis determined by the first and last points. You will be prompted
for the number of sides. Add points by clicking on the screen. Each time you
add a point, a line is connected from the last point to the new one. Click twice
on a point to open a pop up menu with options. The options are to move a point, 
spin the object, and abort the operation.

The spun object is actually a separate object - it is not part of the object
you were working with. This is because it is rare that a spun object will be
exactly where you want it in space. By making it a separate object, it is
separate from everything else and it can be easily positioned with the Move and
Transform options in the Object menu. Then, once it is positioned correctly, use
the Combine command in the Object menu to make it part of another object.

Sliced: Use this to create an object that is made of equally spaced slices.
This is sometimes called "lofting". A window will prompt you for the number of
slices and the distance between each.

				101

Then, you draw the outline of the first slice by clicking on the screen. To
access options, click on a point and a pop up menu will appear, prompting to add a
slice, move a point, or abort the operation. When you add the first slice, the
first and last points will automatically be joined to make the base of the
sliced object complete. Then, you can build the sliced object up by moving
points and adding slices, until the top is added.

3-Demon does its best to fill in the polygon at the base and top of the sliced
object, but for complex shapes, it often misses a triangle or two.

Like spinning an object, slicing an object creates a new, unique, object.

Back Faces: Each triangle can only be viewed from one side. If you'd like the
other side visible, you can create a triangle that is identical, just facing in
the other direction.

