ADDING TO AN OBJECT

Suppose you want to add more to your spun object. It needs more faces,  maybe a
line or two to turn it into that butterfly you had it mind. It's easy to add
new triangles and lines to the object. However, there are a few things to
understand first.

Creating triangles is done simply in a point and click fashion. Click three
times and you have created the three points that define a triangle.

It's actually not that simple. The mouse can only describe a two dimensional
triangle. We need depth information to describe a three dimensional triangle.

Enter the Depth View. Imagine that there is a sheet of clear glass placed
across the view so that you are looking directly at it. Anything that is drawn
is drawn on this sheet of glass. If the glass is brought closer to you, then
when new triangles are created on it, they are also closer because they are
drawn on that glass.

The depth of this sheet of glass is set with the Distance slider.

So, to create a triangle at a particular place, orient the view so that the
triangle will face you and set the Distance slider for the proper depth.

Almost always an object is made up of triangles that butt up against each other
and share edges. Since the edges of triangles are really defined by two
points, sharing edges means sharing points. So, if you are attaching a new
triangle to an object, you may wish to connect it to existing points.

This is easily done. Remember that all points within the Grab Range are
highlighted. If you are constructing a triangle and you click on a highlighted
point, instead of creating a new point, 3-Demon will use that point as a corner
of your triangle, even though it may not be at the depth of the Distance slider.

