3-DEMON FILE FORMAT

3-Demon files are in binary, so it's just about impossible to edit them by hand.

So, this chapter is intended only for serious programmers who are interested in
writing software that can read and write the 3-Demon format.

The 3-Demon file format supports 7 different chunk types:

SURF - Surface descriptor list. Each object has a list of these, describing
different colors and surface characteristics. The list can be any length but
must have at least one surface.

VRTX - A vertex list. Each vertex carries the data to describe a point in 3D
space, and each also points to a surface descriptor. Each object has a list of
vertices.

TRNG - Triangle list. Each object has a list of triangles. Each triangle points
to three vertices (unless it is a line, in which case it points to only two) and a
surface descriptor.

OPTR - A matrix operation list. Each object can have a list of mathematical
transformations. The list can be any length. There are three types of operation:
ROTATE, SCALE, and TRANSLATE.

TRAN - A transformation header. This structure carries the operation list and
additional transformation information (which, for reasons that only made sense in
the earlier versions of the program include the name of the object that owns
this transformation list.)

OBJT - An object. If an object has children, they are all embedded recursively
within the parent object. Each object has lists of vertices, triangles and
surfaces, and a transformation structure and list of transformation operations.

SCNE - Finally, an entire scene. This carries all of the objects and all user
definable parameters that effect the display (for example, the position of the
eye and screen icons.)

The format isn't too different from an IFF format. Each chunk type is
introduced with a four byte identifier ("SURF",  "VRTX", etc.) followed

				129

by a byte count of the chunk. If a reader isn't familiar with a chunk type,  it
can simply skip over it.

There is no "FORM" or file type information at the start of the file, rather
just the identifier for the first chunk which must have everything else
embedded in it. So, when a scene is saved from the Project menu, the file we save
is entirely a SCNE chunk. Saving an object from the Object menu creates a file
that is an OBJT chunk.

SURFACES

Every object must save at least one Surface, so that all Triangles and Vertices
can point to it.

The Surface chunk starts off with a header that describes the size of each
surface item (so later releases can support more fields) and how many items there
are. Then, the list of surfaces follows. There are two fields (rgb and renumber)
that just ended up in the file because the whole Surface structure gets copied.
Don't worry about what you stick in those fields when writing.

Some of the surface parameters aren't used by 3-Demon. All of the information
about how the surface reflects light isn't touched by 3-Demon. However, 
different rendering programs use different combinations of these and the
intention is to give the user the opportunity to define what the renderer
should do, even though there is no feedback within the editor.

BYTES	NAME			DESCRIPTION

4	"SURF"			Chuck header
4	length			Size of chunk
4	item size		Size of each surface descriptor
4	item count		Number of surfaces
2	id			Id of first surface (count from 0 up.)
2	rgb			RGB of color
2	register		Register that displays this (ignore.)
2	special id		Number for special surface type.
1	red			Red value, between 0 and 255.
1	green			Green value, between 0 and 255.
1	blue			Blue value, between 0 and 255.
1	ambient light		Ambient light, from 0 to 255.
1	diffuse reflection   	Diffuse reflection, 0 to 255.

				130

1	specular reflection	Specular reflection, 0 to 255.
1	Metalicity		0 if dull, 255 for sharp highlights.
1	refraction		Reflection index for material 0-255.
1	opacity			How opaque this surface is.
30	name			Each surface has a name.
1	reflection		0=non reflective, 255=mirror.
2	id			Id of next surface....

VERTICES

Prior to saving the Triangle list, a list of Vertices is saved.

The Vertex chunk starts off with a header that describes the size of each
vertex item (so later releases can support more fields) and how many items there
are. Then, the list of vertices follows.

The coordinates of the points are stored as fixed point numbers. The high word
hold the integer value, while the low word is the fraction. However, 3-Demon at
this point does not support the fractional part so we effectively have 16 bit
integers shifted left 16 bits. This does provide a safe upgrade path to higher
resolutions.

BYTES	NAME		DESCRIPTION

4	"VRTX"		Chunk header
4	length		Size of chunk
4	item size	Size of each vertex.
4	item count	Number of vertices.
2	id		Id of first vertex (count from 0 up.)
2	surface		Id of surface this points to.
4	X		X coordinate (integer).
4	Y		Y coordinate (integer).
4	Z		Z coordinate (integer).
2	id		Next vertex....

TRIANGLES

The Triangle chunk starts off with a header that describes the size of each
triangle item (so later releases can support more fields) and how many items
there are. Then, the list of triangles follows.

				131

This can also describe a line. If the 'type' field is clear, this is a line and
the vertices that compose it are the first two. If this is a triangle,  'type'
is 1.

The ordering of vertices is critical because whether the vertices are viewed
clockwise or counterclockwise determines whether we are looking at the front or
back face of the triangle. 3-Demon does not display the back face. If you are
writing triangles that come out invisible, simply flip two vertices and they
will face out properly.

BYTES	NAME		DESCRIPTION

4	"TRNG"		Chunk header
4	length		Size of chunk
4	item size	Size of each triangle
4	item count	Number of triangles.
2	vertex a	Id of first vertex this points to.
2	vertex b	Id of second vertex this points to.
2	vertex c	Id of third vertex this points to.
2	surface		Id of surface this points to.
2	poly id		Ignore.
1	type		Triangle=1, Line=0.
2	vertex a	Next triangle....

OPERATIONS

It's not required that these be supported. However, if the user saves an object
that has some radical transformations applied to it, reading without taking
these into consideration could result an object that is an odd shape. So, it
would be good to apply the transformations to the object while reading it in, if
nothing else. The transformations are ordered in the list in the order they are
applied to the object. This is important! If you apply transformations in a
different order, their effect will probably change.

The Operation list chunk starts off with a header that describes the size of
each Operation item and how many items there are. Then, the list of operations
follows.

Each Operation is composed of a command and three long word parameters.
Depending on the operation, the data type of the parameters change: For ROTATE, 
the parameters are angles with a degree range of 0 to 256, integer. For SCALE, 
the parameters are three scaling constants in fast floating point

				132

format. For TRANSLATE, they are fixed point numbers (integers shifted left 16
with a fractional lower 16 bits.)

BYTES	NAME		DESCRIPTION

4	"OPTR"		Chunk header
4	length		Size of chunk
4	item size	Size of each operation.
4	item count	Number of operations.
4	x		X parameter.
4	y		Y parameter.
4	z		Z parameter.
2	command		ROTATE=1, TRANSLATE=4, SCALE=6.
4	x		Next operation....

TRANSFORMATION HEADER

Each operation list belongs to a Transformation header.

This has a name, the transformation list, and a padding of 128 bytes. The name is
actually the name of the object that owns this transformation list.

BYTES		NAME		DESCRIPTION

4		"TRAN"		Chunk header
4		length		Size of chunk
4		item size	Size of transformation data.
10		name		Name.
128		pad		Ignore this.
OPTR size 	operation list  The operation list (see above.)

OBJECT

An object is composed of a list of vertices, a list of surfaces, a list of
triangles, a transformation structure and its list of operations, and a list of
child objects. With this version, there is no additional information that
pertains just to the object, though a variable length field is included for that
purpose.

Although the reader can read the lists in any order, some ordering is important.
The Surface list must precede the Triangle and Vertex lists. Likewise, the
Vertex list must precede the Triangle list.

				133

There must be at least one Surface, although there need not be any Vertices or
Triangles (pointless, though...)

There should be a transform header, if for no other purpose than to supply the
object's name.

There can be zero or more child objects.

BYTES		NAME		DESCRIPTION

4		"OBJT"		Chunk header
4		length		Size of chunk
4		item size	Size of object data (currently 0, none follows.)
0		object data	Empty.
TRAN size	transform header  Transform header chunk.
SURF size	surface list	Surface list chunk.
VERT size	vertex list	Vertex list chunk.
TRNG size	triangle list	Triangle list chunk.
OBJT size	child object	Child object chunk.
OBJT size	child object	Another child object chunk.

When an object is saved as a file, the file name has the extension ".object"
added to it.

SCENE

A Scene is the whole project, which would be all of the objects and a bunch of
data about the current viewing environment.

If you are writing a program that can read and write 3-Demon objects, it might
be best to simply deal with the object format. There isn't much to be gained by
loading and saving scenes since all of the additional data is very 3-Demon
specific. However, if you'd like to be able to read Scenes, it's not that hard.
Ignore the Scene data and read in all of the objects. To save a Scene, set the
Scene data buffer length to 0, so 3-Demon won't replace preset parameters with
potentially dangerous garbage. Then, save your objects one by one.

The SCNE chunk starts off with the size of the entire chunk, followed by the
size of the Scene data, then the Scene data, then the Objects.

BYTES		NAME		DESCRIPTION

4		"SCNE"		Chunk header
4		length		Size of chunk
4		item size	Size of Scene data.
scene data size scene data	Ignore when reading, avoid writing.
OBJT size	object		First object chunk.
OBJT size	object		Another object chunk.
OBJT size	object		And so on...

Scene files end with ".3demon".

