GLOSSARY

BACK FACE: A triangle has two sides. In 3-Demon, only one side is displayed. This
makes sense most of the time. For example, a sphere object has all of its
triangles facing outward. The back sides of all of the triangles that make up
the skin of the sphere face inwards, where nobody can see them. These are called
Back Faces. In other cases, a back face is seen, an obvious example being a
triangle floating alone in space. However, 3-Demon will still only display one
side of the triangle. Rotate around the triangles and it disappears.

COORDINATE: At the lowest level, everything in 3D space is described by points.
An object is made up of triangles. A triangle is described by three points.
Each point, in turn is described by three numbers. These numbers are its
distance from the origin along the three axes, X, Y, and Z. These three numbers
are called the "coordinates" of the point.

DEPTH VIEW: 3-Demon's primary display is the Main View. This provides a head on
shot of the object. To give a better feel for how far an object is from the
viewer, the Depth View shows the same scene as viewed from above.

DRAG RANGE: The Drag Range is the range of distance from the viewer within which
you can grab points. Points that are outside of the drag range are either too
close or too far. Points within the drag range are drawn in the Main View, the
rest are not. The Drag Range is depicted in the Depth View as the are between
two "fog banks" of white dots.

EDGES: In 3-Demon, there is a distinction between Edges and Lines. The term Edge
refers to the border of a triangle. An Edge is not a distinct entity in its
own right. A Line is.

FLAT VIEWS: The flat views screen lets you edit an object as two orthographic
projections. In other words, there are two views, one which draws the object with
the Z component of each point missing, the other draws with the Y components
missing. This has the advantage of absolutely no perspective distortion (see
Projection).

HIERARCHY: A useful way to organize objects is a HIERARCHY. In a HIERARCHY, one
object is a parent of several more objects, each of which might be a parent of
even more. And so it progresses down the tree, much like a pyramid. Anything
done to a parent object (move it, save it to disk, etc.) affects all of its
children and grandchildren. The reverse is not so.

				136

HUE: A color can be described in part by its Hue. The hue is the angle in the
color wheel of the color. Hue is used in conjunction with Intensity and
Saturation.

INTENSITY: Intensity is used in conjunction with Hue and Saturation to describe
a color. The intensity of a color is analogous to a light fader. As the
intensity is turned down, the color fades to black.

LINE: Like a Triangle, a Line is a primitive out of which objects are made. And, 
like a triangle, a line can have a surface, the surface is used to draw just the
line.

MAIN VIEW: This is the primary 3-Demon display. It fills up most of the Amiga's
screen and displays the objects that are being worked on.

ORIGIN: The Origin is the center of the 3D world. It has X, Y, and Z coordinates
of 0, 0, 0. It is where the three axes meet.

PERSPECTIVE: See Projection.

POINT: A Point describes a specific location in 3D space. A Point is described
by three coordinates, one for each of the X, Y, and Z axes. There is no other
article in 3-Demon that does this. Both triangles and lines are described
physically by what their endpoints are. If a point moves, the triangle goes with
it. A powerful use of this is the concept of Shared Points, where two or more
triangles share a point. When the point is moved, all triangles that use it bend
with it. This provides much of the power and flexibility of 3-Demon editing.

PROJECTION: Projection is the process of taking a three dimensional object and
putting it on a two dimensional screen, such as the Amiga's.

An orthographic, or flat, projection, of which there are two in Flat Views, simply
draws the picture as if one of the dimensions (X, Y, or Z) is gone.

A perspective projection, which is what the Main View display is, draws objects
from the point of view of an imaginary eye. Objects that are close to the eye
are drawn large, while objects that are far are drawn small. If the objects are
very close to the eye, the difference between near and far becomes very
pronounced and we get a fish eye effect. This is also called perspective
distortion.

REFLECTION: Reflection is a property of a surface. It describes how much of the
light that hits the surface bounces back off of it, is reflected. A very
reflective surface, for example day-glo paint, is bright.

				137

REFRACTION: Refraction is a property of transparent materials. Light bends when
it goes through one transparent material and into another. This is called
refraction.

RENDERING: This is the computational process of taking the description of a
three dimensional scene and creating a two dimensional image. 3-Demon renders
the image in the Main View by computing where all the triangles should be, 
computing shading if required, and drawing the triangles.

ROTATION: See Transformation.

SATURATION: Saturation is used in conjunction with Hue and Intensity to describe
a color. Saturation describes how bold and distinct a color is. As the
saturation is turned down, the color takes on more and more of a gray tone as it
looses its identity.

SCALE: The term Scale is used in several different situations within 3-Demon. In
all cases, the operation of scaling something makes it larger or smaller. The
view might be scaled to "zoom in" or "zoom out", or an object might be scaled to
make it larger or smaller.

SCENE: In 3-Demon, the entire working environment is composed of all objects
loaded, the viewing parameters, and all options that have been set by the user.
This is also called the Scene.

SHADING: When an object is rendered, simply painting all triangles directly with
the colors that are described for them rarely results in a satisfying sight.
This is because in the real world differently angled sides catch different
amounts of light and so are lighter or darker because of it. Recreating this
effect is called Shading.

In rendering programs, shading can get quite sophisticated. You define where one
or more light sources are and how intense each is. Then, the program calculates
how bright or dark each side should be and draws them accordingly.

3-Demon has a less sophisticated, gray scale shading scheme. This assumes there
are two fixed light sources at opposite sides of the object. Any side that
directly faces one of the light sources at a 90 degree angle is painted white.
As the angle moves away, the sides become progressively darker, reaching black at
180 degrees. For 3-Demon's needs, this is very adequate. It provides a strong
feeling for the curvature of the surface, enhancing the three dimensional feel
and thereby making editing easier.

SURFACE: A Surface is used to describe how a particular item reflects light. Some
programs use the term "texture" to describe the same thing.

				138

In 3-Demon, a surface describes a color and has a group of parameters, like
Ambient Reflection, that describe how it reflects light. Every triangle, line, and
point in 3-Demon is painted with a surface.

TRANSFORMATION: A Transformation is a mathematical operation that can be
performed on a point, changing it. There are three transformations that are of
particular interest in graphics work:

	Move, or translation, adds offsets to the X, Y, and Z values of the point.
	This simply shifts an object in space.

	Scale multiplies the point by a number, making it closer or farther from
	the origin, thereby shrinking or stretching it.

	Rotate alters the position of the point by rotating it about the origin
	by some specified angle. By transforming the group of points that
	define an object, we end up transforming the object itself.

VERTEX: See Point.

